I've posted up many of the interesting murals the team at Saint John's Church on Princes Street create. Many, including their Christmas and Easter ones, still carry social and political and moral commentary (a favourite was a Christmas one few years ago, painting of cash register, shoppers and "glory to God in the High Street"). Often they are as clever and interesting as the best editorial cartoons in the newspapers, and I love that they put them up in the shadow of the Castle facing one of the busiest streets in the capital.

This year's though is fairly simple, just a lovely portrait of Nelson Mandela and that smile. Simple, elegant but a nice reminder there is always hope in the darkest times, that the dawn always comes but we have to work to make that dawn happens and for all to share in that rising light and warmth. With so many people in our 'economic recovery' relying on charity food banks and losing their homes while multi millionaire cabinet ministers tell us we must make cuts and sacrifices (I don't see them doing that) it's important to remember that. And for those of us for whom this time of year brings sad memories of the gaps at the Christmas table, the loved ones gone forever and how we feel that ache more keenly at this time of year, again we need to remember the sun will rise again, the wheel will turn, and we need to keep trying. It's bloody hard sometimes, I know that all too well, but we owe it to ourselves, to those we loved and lost and to our fellow beings on this remarkable world shining in the dark of space to try. Merry Christmas, folks.

We had our annual Christmas trip around Edinburgh today, Mum and me. Normally it's on her birthday but as we'll be away then we went round today instead. Mum loves Christmas. She loves Christmas, primarily, I think, because she hates the dark. All those northern hemisphere, mid-winter festivals are just bonkers about light. My good, solid, post-modern education taught me to distrust dichotomies. Sure, there are deep and dangerous outcomes from a light-good, dark-bad mindset. Sure, we need the darkness as much as we need the light (you're speaking to a woman who grew up with shutters in the country and so now sleeps with a pillow on her face to eradicate all-night-city light). But as I watch the sun crawl up onto the roof of St Aloysius, pech its way across for a couple of hours and then gladly head back down to bed in the earth just after lunch, I love to turn on the multicoloured lights in the kitchen, or to light the fire at home, or to plooter along Princes Street and see the trees all decked in stars. 

I am thankful for sky sun, and human sun. And one day I will have a SAD lamp and my life will change.

Very cute little back street I never knew existed. Two or three little rows of small but now desirable fisherman's cottages. These ones are set back from the seafront with two other similar rows of houses between them and the sea. But there's a steep bank behind them, so there's probably not much sun reaches the back windows at some times of the year..
One in the row facing these was for sale for £195,000 ($300,000)
From the road above the seafront cottages. (Granton Road) Wardie Square is just off to the right. A main road, Lower Granton Road, runs along the front of the terrace.

description._content: close up on one of the decorations on the Dome

Christmas tree in Charlotte Square, one of the two large squares at either end of the Georgian era New Town. In this spot during August the world's largest literary bash, the Edinburgh International Book Festival takes place, with hundreds of authors and events (I've been lucky enough to chair a few myself), but at this time of year it is just a garden in the square with a Christmas tree.

Had to muck around a bit to get a photo - there are railings all around and the gardens are private so you can't get in outside of festival time without a key. Railing too high to shoot over with the tripod even cranked up to max height, so tilted camera on its side, lens pointing between railings, zoom in to cut them out, et voila...

Another shot of the Castle at night, this time taken from down in Princes Street Gardens, which let me get an angle to have part of the Castle in plus the ultra expensive Ramsay Gardens apartments (on the lower left of the Castle) and the big Christmas tree on the Mound.

Spent last three hours walking around town taking night shots of the city and pics of the festive markets and decorations. Tired out, hungry, but before dinner am posting one pic, will check through the rest and post any half decent ones later, but pleased with this one. Sun has set about twenty minutes before I arrived at this spot, but the western sky was splashed with the most magnificent reds and purples, silhouetting the floodlit rocky bulk of Edinburgh Castle atop the mighty Castle Rock. Struggled to get a vantage point without trees in the way from where I was, several shots but all worthless, save for this one. If you look closely at the large version you can even make out people standing on the top battlements looking out across nocturnal Edinburgh, taking in the lights and decorations a few days before Christmas. This was worth all the walking in the cold!

Wandered up Calton Hill, missed most of the sunset but that didnt matter when this developed in front of my eyes.  Edinburgh's Christmas below this awesome sky as seen tonight a little after 4pm.

The massive, soaring "Gothic Rocket" of the Scott Monument, currently during the festive season joined by this tall fairground ride next to it, like an old chair-o-plane ride on steroids as before the wheel rotates and spins out the chairs on hanging chains it rises very, very high in the air.

Looking up towards the Mound from a Princes Street Gardens busy with the festive crowd in the Christmas market and fair. On the bottom you can see the underground flank of the National Gallery of Scotland - the gallery itself is in a large, neo-Classical building but it extends below the plaza in front of it with more gallery space, conference rooms and restaurant. The cafe and restaurant windows which are under the plaza have windows along one side facing down into the valley where the Gardens are (those are the large, bright windows you can see along the bottom). Above on the Mound you can see stalls from the festive market and on the centre and right at the top the other large neo-Classical building which domiantes the Mound, sitting in front of the National Gallery (and connected to it by that underground section), the Royal Scottish Academy

Edinburgh University's Old College houses parts of the University's administration, the University of Edinburgh School of Law, and the Talbot Rice Gallery. Originally called the "New College", it was designed by Robert Adam in 1789 to replace earlier buildings.

Adam unfortunately died in 1792 with less than a quarter of the scheme built. W H Playfair was appointed in 1816 to complete the buildings. He reorganised Adam's scheme, which was completed around 1820. As funds ran out, the courtyard was never completed and paved. 

Architects Simpson & Brown was approached in 2005 by the University to complete the scheme. Their historical research established that there were no original drawings, so the paving, in Hazeldean stone, was designed closely following the precedents of Playfair's other Edinburgh buildings. A central grassed area was also incorporated to soften the space, and make it more suitable for events and performances.

Jollie’s Close in Edinburgh dates back to the earlier 17th century and was named after Patrick Jollie then later, in 1859, after a writer Alexander Jollie.   

Inside there is a 3-storey and attic rubble-built tenement with stairtower dating to 1635 that now is part of The Witchery suites.  Built on the site of the Palace of Mary de Guise, mother of Mary Queen of Scots, these buildings have variously been the townhouse of an aristocratic family and part of the University's Faculty of Divinity before their recent restoration.
